I shot several different bullet, sabot, powder combinations and settled on the combination as follows: Barnes Original 300gr bullet, Harvester black crush rib sabot, and 70grs of Alliant Reloder 10X smokeless powder ignited by a CCI 209 shotgun primer. This combination shot very consistently and showed a velocity of 2505fps average over the chronograph. I was shooting at 100 yards and sighted in both your scope and your open sights. This load shoots about 1 1/2""-2"" high at 100 yards and should be dead on at around 200-225 yards. If I got a shot out around 300 yards, I would probably hold about 4"" high and expect a clean kill! I've enclosed a photo of the last target that I shot. Also with the target you will see the Barnes bullets and Harvester sabots that I settled on as the best combination for this rifle. This Barnes original 300gr bullet  at 2500fps will cleanly kill any North American big game animal including the big bears. I removed and re-installed the scope and then shot it once again to check point of impact. This scope returns to zero as well as any if have ever shot and I really couldn't tell that it had been off of the rifle at all.    Just wipe down the outside of the rifle and keep it in a cool, dry climate till the next time you want to shoot it. It is practically maintenance free if you keep it dry. When shooting this rifle, you will notice that this particular bullet/sabot combination takes a great deal of force (40-50lbs or so) to get it loaded down the bore, and then an extra effort to seat it tightly on the powder. That is a good thing with these rifles and improves accuracy and reliability.  It really is a super safe rifle though and you can learn a lot just by reading the manual. The only variation that you will be applying different than the manual is our choice of powder, bullet and sabot. Other than that, all of the book recommendations apply.

474,http://www.armslist.com/posts/3924474,For Sale:  Kel Tec KSG 12 Guage Shotgun 14+1 Bullpup Shotgun *OD Green Edition*,"Simi Valley, Los Angeles, California","$ 1,100","Listed On: Tuesday, March 31, 2015",Shotguns,no type,12 Gauge                                                                                ,Pump Action                                                                                ,Shotgun,"Kel Tec KSG 12 Guage Shotgun 14+1 Bullpup Shotgun *OD Green Edition*!

The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4"" up to the 3"".
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward."

733,http://www.armslist.com/posts/3924733,For Sale:  Remington Model 30 Express 30-06,"Enterprise, Dothan, Alabama",$ 420,"Listed On: Friday, January 23, 2015",Rifles,Remington                                                                                ,30-06 Springfield                                                                                ,Bolt Action                                                                                ,Rifle,"*** Rare Remington Model 30 Express *** Rifle is chambered in 30-06 (“30 Springfield 1906” as stamped on the barrel). Introduction year for the Model 30s was 1921 with a discontinuation year of 1940. The model 30 is a sporting rifle of the inter-war period based on the military P14/M1917 Enfield rifle action, which was manufactured for the British and US governments during WWI. In 1918, after the end of WWI and termination of contracts for both the British P14 and US M1917, Remington was left with two factories (the main factory at llion and the subsidiary at Eddystone) tooled up to make the M1917, and was also left with a large inventory of stored spare parts. It was decided to make a sporting version of the P14/M1917. These were the first high-powered bolt action sporting rifles produced by Remington. If you are a Remington buff, this should grab your attention. Not only is this a great piece of Remington history, these rifles are not easy to come by and very collectable. As always, the gun enthusiasts of the Wiregrass get first shot at this firearm at a most modest price. If no interests shows here, then off to Gun Broker she goes. I am asking $460 for this one.  If you think my price is high, do your research and see what the asking price is on these at the big national sites and compare it to what I am selling this one at (you will only find a handful between Gun Broker and Guns International). Located in Enterprise"

Manufactured in Brooklyn, N.Y., by the Brooklyn Arms Company, the Slocum revolver was a unique design with individual chambers in the form of sliding tubes within cutouts on the cylinder.
